## Diagnosis

The symptom — active label appearing on the **right** side of the rail while hover labels appear on the **left** — points to a **positioning-origin mismatch**. The hover labels and the active label are almost certainly using the same `position: absolute` trick, but they're anchored to **different containing blocks**.

### Why "fixing the anchor element" didn't help

Changing which DOM element you attach to doesn't matter if the `position: absolute` label is still finding a **different nearest positioned ancestor** as its containing block. The real question is: what is each label's containing block, and what `right`/`left` value is being applied?

The classic failure pattern here (AP-072 — *Mismatched Positioning Context*):

```
Rail (position: relative)           ← containing block A
  └── Notch container               ← NOT positioned → transparent
        └── Tick (position: relative) ← containing block B  ← oops
              └── Active label (position: absolute, left: 100%)
                                       resolves relative to the tick,
                                       which is inside the rail,
                                       so "left: 100%" shoots it RIGHT
```

Meanwhile the hover labels are almost certainly:

```
Rail (position: relative)
  └── Hover label (position: absolute, right: 100%)
        resolves relative to the RAIL → appears LEFT of rail ✓
```

The active label is using `left: 100%` (or `translateX(100%)`) relative to the **tick/notch element** rather than `right: 100%` relative to the **rail**, so it ends up to the right instead of joining the left-side gutter.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Mismatched Positioning Context**

The active label's containing block is the notch/tick element (which is itself inside the rail), while all hover labels use the rail as their containing block. The directional offset (`left` vs `right`) is also inverted relative to what the hover labels use.

Two compounded errors:
1. Wrong containing block (tick vs rail)
2. `left: 100%` instead of `right: calc(100% + <gutter>)` relative to the rail

---

## Fix

Assuming a structure similar to this (adjust class names to match yours):

```
components/
  ScrollSpy/
    ScrollSpy.tsx          ← main component
    ScrollSpyRail.tsx      ← the vertical rail
    ScrollSpyItem.tsx      ← per-section notch + label
```

### Step 1 — `ScrollSpyRail.tsx` (or wherever the rail is rendered)

Make sure the rail is the explicit positioning root and has enough left-side overflow room:

```tsx
// ScrollSpyRail.tsx
export function ScrollSpyRail({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <div
      // Rail is the single positioning root for ALL labels (hover + active)
      className={[
        "relative",          // ← containing block for every absolute label
        "flex flex-col",
        "items-center",
        // give the left gutter room so labels don't clip the viewport
        "ml-auto",           // pushed to right edge of sidebar
      ].join(" ")}
    >
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Step 2 — `ScrollSpyItem.tsx` — the critical fix

The notch/tick **must not** be `position: relative` (or any positioned value) unless you explicitly want it to be a containing block. Remove positioning from the tick and let both labels resolve against the rail.

```tsx
// ScrollSpyItem.tsx
interface ScrollSpyItemProps {
  label: string;
  isActive: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
}

export function ScrollSpyItem({ label, isActive, onClick }: ScrollSpyItemProps) {
  return (
    // This wrapper must NOT be position:relative — let the rail be the root
    <div className="relative w-full flex items-center justify-center group">

      {/* ─── Notch / tick mark ───────────────────────────────────────────
          No `relative` here. It's just a visual dot inside the rail.     */}
      <button
        onClick={onClick}
        aria-label={label}
        className={[
          // ❌ Do NOT add `relative` or `absolute` to this element
          "w-2 h-2 rounded-full transition-colors",
          isActive
            ? "bg-foreground scale-125"
            : "bg-muted-foreground/40 hover:bg-muted-foreground",
        ].join(" ")}
      />

      {/* ─── Hover label (always present, shown on group-hover) ──────────
          Anchored RIGHT edge → rail's left edge via `right: 100%`        */}
      {!isActive && (
        <span
          className={[
            "absolute",
            "right-[calc(100%+0.75rem)]",  // ← left of rail, in the gutter
            "whitespace-nowrap",
            "text-xs text-muted-foreground",
            "opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100",
            "transition-opacity pointer-events-none",
            "text-right",                   // text aligns toward the rail
          ].join(" ")}
        >
          {label}
        </span>
      )}

      {/* ─── Active label (replaces hover label when active) ─────────────
          SAME anchor logic as hover label: right: 100% + gutter          */}
      {isActive && (
        <span
          className={[
            "absolute",
            "right-[calc(100%+0.75rem)]",  // ← IDENTICAL to hover label ✓
            "whitespace-nowrap",
            "text-xs font-semibold text-foreground",
            "text-right",
            // no opacity trick needed — always visible when active
          ].join(" ")}
          aria-current="true"
        >
          {label}
        </span>
      )}

    </div>
  );
}
```

### Step 3 — If you use a separate active-label overlay (common pattern)

If the active label is rendered **outside** the item loop (e.g., a single floating element that moves with `top` set via JS), it **must** also be a child of the rail element, not of `document.body` or a portal:

```tsx
// ScrollSpy.tsx  — the orchestrator
export function ScrollSpy({ sections }: ScrollSpyProps) {
  const [activeIdx, setActiveIdx] = useState(0);

  return (
    //                     ↓ rail is the positioning root
    <ScrollSpyRail>
      {sections.map((s, i) => (
        <ScrollSpyItem
          key={s.id}
          label={s.label}
          isActive={i === activeIdx}
          onClick={() => scrollTo(s.id)}
        />
      ))}

      {/*
        If you use a SINGLE traveling active label instead of per-item:
        Keep it here, inside the rail, and use the same right-offset.
      */}
      {/* <ActiveLabelTracker sections={sections} activeIdx={activeIdx} /> */}
    </ScrollSpyRail>
  );
}
```

---

## Why the previous "anchor element" fix didn't work

Changing from tick → notch container made no difference because **both elements are inside the same mis-positioned subtree**. The label was still finding the tick (or notch) as its containing block because it was `position: absolute` inside a `position: relative` tick. The fix is to **remove all `relative`/`absolute` positioning from the notch element** entirely so the absolute label skips past it and latches onto the rail.

---

## Principle

> **Single positioning root per component group.**  
> Every element that must share a coordinate space (hover labels, active label, tick marks) should resolve against **one** explicitly declared `position: relative` ancestor. Any intermediate element that inadvertently becomes `position: relative` silently creates a new containing block and breaks the alignment contract. When labels appear on the wrong side, the first question is always *"what is this element's actual containing block?"* — not *"which child am I attached to?"*
